-- cell-zero.cell: the evaluation kernel for Cell
--
-- Built backwards from the sink node. Each cell exists because
-- something downstream needs it. The dependency graph IS the design.
--
-- [ENV] = substrate-provided (fixed interface, swappable body)
-- [CRYST] = crystallization candidate (∴ now, ⊢= eventually)
-- [PERM-SOFT] = permanently soft (requires LLM forever)
--
-- Three acceptance oracles on the sink define "cell-zero works."
-- Everything else exists to satisfy them.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 0: THE SINK
-- "cell-zero works" = these three oracles pass
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ run
  given program-path
  given eval-loop→§final-state
  yield §quiescent-state

  ⊢= §quiescent-state ← eval-loop→§final-state

  ⊨ no cell in §quiescent-state is ready
  ⊨ every frozen yield in §quiescent-state passed its oracles
  ⊨ every ⊥ in §quiescent-state traces to exhaustion or ⊥?-handler


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 0: PROGRAM LOADING
-- run needs a §graph. That means reading + parsing.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ load                                                         -- [ENV]
  given run→program-path
  yield contents

  ∴ Read the file at «program-path» and return its text.

  ⊨ contents is a string or ⊥ (file not found)

  -- single-claude: human pastes the file
  -- hybrid:        ⊢= contents ← fs.read(program-path)
  -- gastown:       ⊢= contents ← git.show(program-path)

⊢ parse                                                        -- [CRYST]
  given load→contents
  yield §graph

  ∴ Parse «contents» as a Cell program.
    Extract cell declarations (⊢ ⊢= ⊢⊢ ⊢∘), dependency edges
    (given/yield), oracles (⊨), guards (where), handlers (⊥?).
    Return the full graph structure.

  ⊨ each cell in §graph.cells has: name, kind, givens[], yields[], body, oracles[], guards[]
  ⊨ each edge in §graph.edges has: from-cell, from-field, to-cell, to-field
  ⊨ no duplicate cell names in §graph

  -- This is THE crystallization target. When parse becomes ⊢=,
  -- cell-zero has bootstrapped its own parser. That's Phase 5.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 0: THE LOOP
-- eval-loop is a ⊢⊢ spawner. It iterates eval-step until
-- no cells are ready. State threads across iterations.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ init-state
  given parse→§graph
  yield §state

  ⊢= §state ← { graph: §graph, frozen: {}, bindings: {} }

  ⊨ §state.frozen is empty
  ⊨ §state.graph = §graph

⊢⊢ eval-loop
  given init-state→§state
  yield §final-state
  until eval-step→§state-out where find-ready→ready = []
  max 10000

  ∴ Repeatedly: find ready cells, pick one, evaluate it,
    check oracles, commit or retry, handle ⊥, update state.
    Each iteration consumes §state-in and produces §state-out.
    Stop when no cells are ready (quiescence).

  ⊨ §final-state extends init-state→§state (monotonicity: only adds bindings)
  ⊨ §final-state preserves all values frozen in any prior iteration


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 1: ONE EVAL STEP
-- eval-step is the unit of work. It takes a state in and
-- produces a state out with exactly one cell advanced.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ find-ready                                                   -- [CRYST]
  given §state
  yield ready[], blocked[]

  ∴ For each cell in «§state.graph.cells»:
    - Resolve all given references against «§state.bindings»
    - Evaluate guard clauses (where) against frozen values
    - Cell is READY if: all givens bound, all guards true, not yet frozen
    - Cell is BLOCKED if: any given unbound or any guard false
    - If a given references ⊥: check for given? (optional) or ⊥? handler

  ⊢= ready ← filter(§state.graph.cells, c =>
    all(c.givens, g => bound(g, §state)) and
    all(c.guards, g => eval-guard(g, §state)) and
    not frozen(c, §state))

  ⊨ ready ∪ blocked = all non-frozen cells in §state.graph
  ⊨ every cell in ready has all givens bound in §state

  -- Both ∴ and ⊢= bodies shown. The ⊢= is the crystallized form.
  -- In single-claude mode, the LLM uses the ∴.
  -- In hybrid/gastown mode, the runtime uses the ⊢=.
  -- The ⊨ oracles hold for BOTH.

⊢ pick-cell                                                    -- [CRYST]
  given find-ready→ready
  yield §target

  ∴ Choose one cell from «ready». Prefer cells with fewer
    unresolved dependencies (leaf-first). If tied, any choice
    is valid — confluence guarantees same final result.

  ⊨ §target ∈ find-ready→ready

  -- Crystallized form is topological sort. Any valid choice works.
  -- gastown: this is where priority/assignment logic could plug in


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 1: DISPATCH
-- The heart of cell-zero. Dispatch looks at the target cell's
-- kind and routes to the appropriate evaluator.
--
-- THIS IS WHERE § BECOMES STRUCTURALLY NECESSARY.
-- Dispatch must construct cell definitions (for spawners,
-- claims, handlers) and insert them into the graph.
--
-- THIS IS WHERE RECURSION BECOMES STRUCTURALLY NECESSARY.
-- Dispatch encountering ⊢∘ needs eval-loop. Check-claims
-- needs dispatch. Cell-zero must invoke itself.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ dispatch                                                     -- [PERM-SOFT]
  given pick-cell→§target
  given §state
  yield tentative-outputs, §graph-updates[]

  ∴ Evaluate «§target» based on its kind:
    - ⊢ with ∴ body  → invoke-substrate (semantic eval)
    - ⊢ with ⊢= body → eval-expression (deterministic)
    - ⊢⊢ (spawner)   → spawn-children (§ construction + graph insert)
    - ⊢∘ (evolution)  → evolution-loop (recursive eval-loop!)
    - ⊢∘ co-evolve    → co-evolution-loop (recursive, parallel)

    For ∴ bodies: resolve «» interpolations from §state.bindings,
    send to substrate, receive tentative output.

    For ⊢= bodies: evaluate the expression using the ⊢= calculus.

    For ⊢⊢: construct new §cell-definitions from the spawner's
    template and add them to §graph-updates.

    For ⊢∘: enter a sub-eval-loop over the target cell, threading
    through the `through` chain, checking `until`, respecting `max`.

  ⊨ |tentative-outputs| = |§target.yields|
  ⊨ §graph-updates are well-formed cell definitions (if any)
  ⊨ dispatch is total: every cell kind is handled


-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
-- dispatch delegates to these sub-cells:
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

⊢ invoke-substrate                                             -- [ENV]
  given §target, §state
  given §target.body where §target.kind = "soft"
  yield response

  ∴ Resolve all «» interpolations in «§target.body» using
    «§state.bindings». Send the resolved prompt to the semantic
    substrate. Return the response.

  ⊨ response is compatible with §target.yields

  -- single-claude: LLM reads the ∴ body in-context and produces output
  -- hybrid:        ⊢= response ← api.call(resolve(§target.body, §state))
  -- gastown:       ⊢= response ← sling(§target, polecat) |> await
  --
  -- In gastown, confluence means we can sling MULTIPLE ready cells
  -- to different polecats simultaneously. This is parallel eval-one.

⊢ eval-expression                                              -- [CRYST]
  given §target, §state
  given §target.body where §target.kind = "hard"
  yield result

  ∴ Evaluate the ⊢= expression in «§target.body» using the
    defined calculus: arithmetic, comparison, boolean, string ops,
    list ops (filter, map, count, any, all, sort, zip...),
    field access (→), conditionals (if/then/else).
    Resolve all cell references from «§state.bindings».

  ⊢= result ← eval(§target.body, §state.bindings)

  ⊨ result is deterministic given §state.bindings
  ⊨ §target.body uses only ⊢= primitives (no semantic content)

  -- THIS is the ⊢= expression calculus from the spec.
  -- Crystallizing eval-expression = building the expression evaluator.
  -- After crystallization, ⊢= cells never touch the LLM.

⊢ spawn-children                                               -- [CRYST]
  given §target, §state
  given §target where §target.kind = "spawner"
  yield §new-cells[], §new-edges[]

  ∴ Read the spawner template in «§target».
    For each item in the iteration source:
    - Construct a new cell definition (§) from the template
    - Bind the iteration variable
    - Name it according to the spawner's `as` clause (or convention)
    - Generate edges connecting the new cell to the graph

    Respect the spawner mode:
    - accumulate: new cells join existing spawned cells
    - replace: new cells replace previous iteration's cells

  ⊨ each §new-cell has same yields as the spawner template
  ⊨ §new-cells are well-formed cell declarations
  ⊨ no name collisions with existing cells in §state.graph

  -- § IS REQUIRED HERE. spawn-children constructs cell definitions
  -- as data values. Without cell-as-data, spawners cannot work.
  -- This is the first structural requirement for § quotation.

⊢ evolution-loop                                                -- [PERM-SOFT]
  given §target, §state
  given §target where §target.kind = "evolution"
  yield §evolved-outputs, §updated-state

  ∴ Execute a ⊢∘ evolution loop on «§target»:
    1. Evaluate the target cell (via dispatch — RECURSIVE)
    2. Run the `through` chain cells (via dispatch — RECURSIVE)
    3. Check the `until` condition
    4. If met or max reached: return current outputs
    5. If not: re-evaluate target with feedback, go to 1

    For ⊢∘ co-evolve: evaluate all co-targets in parallel on
    iteration 0 with ⊥ for missing peer inputs, then iterate
    with peer outputs available.

    Respect `accumulate`/`replace` for any spawners within.

  ⊨ §evolved-outputs satisfy §target's oracles (aspirational → convergent)
  ⊨ iteration count ≤ §target.max
  ⊨ §target interface (given/yield) preserved across iterations

  -- RECURSION IS REQUIRED HERE. evolution-loop calls dispatch,
  -- which calls eval-step, which IS cell-zero's own eval logic.
  -- This is the metacircular requirement — it falls out of ⊢∘.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 1: ORACLE PROTOCOL
-- After dispatch produces tentative outputs, we check them.
-- This is where § is required AGAIN (claim cell construction)
-- and where dispatch is required AGAIN (claim cell evaluation).
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ spawn-claims                                                 -- [CRYST]
  given §target
  given dispatch→tentative-outputs
  yield §claim-cells[]

  ∴ For each oracle (⊨) on «§target», construct a claim cell:
    - Deterministic oracle → §claim with ⊢= body
    - Structural oracle   → §claim with ⊢= body
    - Semantic oracle     → §claim with ∴ body
    - Conditional oracle  → check antecedent; if false, skip (vacuous pass)

    Each claim cell has:
      given: the tentative outputs + relevant §state bindings
      yield: pass (boolean)
      body:  the oracle check

  ⊨ |§claim-cells| = |§target.oracles| (minus vacuously satisfied conditionals)
  ⊨ each §claim-cell references dispatch→tentative-outputs

  -- § IS REQUIRED HERE (second structural requirement).
  -- spawn-claims constructs cell definitions from oracle assertions.
  -- Oracles ARE cells — this is where that principle becomes concrete.

⊢ check-claims                                                 -- [PERM-SOFT]
  given spawn-claims→§claim-cells
  yield all-pass, failed[], retry-context

  ∴ Evaluate each claim cell in «§claim-cells»:
    - For ⊢= claims: evaluate the expression (deterministic)
    - For ∴ claims: invoke the semantic substrate
    Collect pass/fail results.

  ⊢= all-pass ← all(§claim-cells, c => c.pass)
  ⊢= retry-context ← if all-pass then ""
    else "Failed oracles: " ++ join(filter(§claim-cells, c => not c.pass), ", ")

  ⊨ all-pass ↔ |failed| = 0

  -- DISPATCH IS REQUIRED HERE (second recursive requirement).
  -- Claim cells have bodies (⊢= or ∴). Evaluating them IS dispatch.
  -- check-claims needs cell-zero's own evaluation capability.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 1: COMMIT
-- Decide what to do with the oracle results, then propagate.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ decide                                                       -- [CRYST]
  given check-claims→all-pass
  given check-claims→retry-context
  given dispatch→tentative-outputs
  given §target
  given §state
  yield action, §state-out

  ∴ Based on oracle results for «§target»:

    FREEZE (all-pass = true):
      Bind tentative-outputs as yield ≡ values in §state.
      Mark §target as frozen. Downstream cells may become ready.

    RETRY (all-pass = false, retries remain per ⊨? policy):
      Rewrite §target with «retry-context» appended to its ∴ body.
      Do NOT freeze. Return to find-ready (eval-loop continues).

    BOTTOM (all-pass = false, retries exhausted):
      Freeze §target with all yields = ⊥.
      Apply exhaustion policy: error-value(⊥) or partial-accept.

  ⊢= action ← if all-pass then "freeze"
    else if retries-remaining(§target, §state) > 0 then "retry"
    else "bottom"

  ⊨ action ∈ {"freeze", "retry", "bottom"}
  ⊨ if action = "freeze" then §state-out has new yield ≡ bindings
  ⊨ if action = "bottom" then all yields of §target = ⊥ in §state-out
  ⊨ if action = "retry" then §state-out.frozen = §state.frozen (nothing new frozen)
  ⊨ §state-out extends §state (monotonicity)

⊢ handle-bottom                                                -- [CRYST]
  given decide→§state-out
  given decide→action
  yield §state-after-bottom

  ∴ If «action» = "bottom" or any newly-frozen cell has ⊥ yields:
    For each downstream cell that depends on a ⊥ value:
    - If it has ⊥? skip with: construct a handler cell (§),
      evaluate it, freeze the cell with handler outputs
    - If it has ⊥? error-value(⊥): freeze with ⊥
    - If no ⊥? handler: leave blocked (⊥ propagates naturally)

  ⊨ §state-after-bottom extends decide→§state-out
  ⊨ no cell with a ⊥? handler remains blocked on ⊥ input

  -- § IS REQUIRED HERE (third structural requirement).
  -- handle-bottom constructs handler cells from ⊥? declarations.
  -- ⊥? handlers ARE cells — this is where that principle becomes concrete.

⊢ apply-graph-updates                                          -- [CRYST]
  given dispatch→§graph-updates
  given decide→§state-out
  yield §state-with-new-cells

  ∴ If dispatch produced §graph-updates (from spawners):
    Add new cells and edges to the graph.
    Update the state so find-ready sees them on the next iteration.

  ⊢= §state-with-new-cells ← merge(§state-out,
    { graph: add-cells(§state-out.graph, §graph-updates) })

  ⊨ all cells from §state-out.graph are preserved
  ⊨ new cells are added to §state-with-new-cells.graph
  ⊨ no frozen cells are modified


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 1: EVAL-STEP (composition of one iteration)
-- This cell wires the above into a single step:
-- find → pick → dispatch → claims → decide → bottom → update
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ eval-step
  given §state-in
  yield §state-out

  given find-ready→ready where ready != []
  given pick-cell→§target
  given dispatch→tentative-outputs, dispatch→§graph-updates
  given check-claims→all-pass
  given decide→§state-out as decide-state
  given handle-bottom→§state-after-bottom
  given apply-graph-updates→§state-with-new-cells

  ⊢= §state-out ← apply-graph-updates→§state-with-new-cells

  ⊨ §state-out extends §state-in (monotonicity)
  ⊨ §state-out differs from §state-in by exactly one cell advanced
    (frozen, retried, or ⊥-ed) plus any spawner additions


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 3: CRYSTALLIZATION
-- These cells are what makes cell-zero BECOME a runtime tool.
-- Without them, cell-zero works but stays slow (all ∴, all LLM).
-- With them, deterministic cells graduate to ⊢= and the LLM
-- is only invoked for genuinely semantic work.
--
-- Crystallization is self-application: cell-zero observing its
-- own cells and replacing ∴ with ⊢= where possible.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢ observe-execution                                            -- [CRYST]
  given §target
  given dispatch→tentative-outputs
  given check-claims→all-pass
  yield §execution-record

  ⊢= §execution-record ← {
    cell: §target.name,
    inputs: resolve-inputs(§target, §state),
    outputs: tentative-outputs,
    oracles-passed: all-pass,
    substrate: §target.kind
  }

  ⊨ §execution-record captures complete input→output mapping

  -- Content-addressable: hash(inputs) → outputs.
  -- Same inputs = same hash. If outputs are always the same
  -- for the same hash, the cell is deterministic → crystallizable.

⊢ detect-pattern                                               -- [PERM-SOFT]
  given observe-execution→§execution-record
  given §execution-history                                     -- accumulated records
  yield classification, §candidate-expression

  ∴ Given the execution history for this cell:
    - Are outputs always identical for identical inputs? → "constant"
    - Is there a learnable input→output mapping? → "pattern"
    - Do outputs vary unpredictably? → "semantic"

    If "constant" or "pattern": generate a ⊢= expression that
    reproduces the observed mapping.

  ⊨ classification ∈ {"constant", "pattern", "semantic"}
  ⊨ if classification != "semantic" then §candidate-expression is defined

  -- detect-pattern is permanently soft because generating ⊢=
  -- from observed behavior IS semantic work. This is the
  -- "crystallize" cell from the spec — the stem cell that
  -- can never itself go cold.

⊢ shadow-verify                                                -- [CRYST]
  given detect-pattern→§candidate-expression
  given §target
  given §state
  yield match, §shadow-output

  ∴ Run both the original cell (via dispatch) and the candidate
    ⊢= expression on the same inputs. Compare outputs.

  ⊢= §shadow-output ← eval(§candidate-expression, resolve-inputs(§target, §state))
  ⊢= match ← (§shadow-output = dispatch→tentative-outputs)

  ⊨ shadow-verify does not modify §state (read-only comparison)

⊢ promote                                                      -- [CRYST]
  given shadow-verify→match
  given detect-pattern→§candidate-expression
  given §target
  given §state
  yield §promoted-cell, §state-after-promotion

  ∴ If «match» has been true for N consecutive executions
    (threshold, e.g. 20):
    Replace §target's ∴ body with the candidate ⊢= expression.
    The cell's interface (given/yield/⊨) is preserved.
    The cell's kind changes from "soft" to "hard".

  ⊨ §promoted-cell has same givens and yields as §target
  ⊨ §promoted-cell.oracles = §target.oracles (oracles preserved)
  ⊨ §promoted-cell.kind = "hard"

  -- This is "may replace" from the spec — permission, not equality.
  -- The ∴ body is never discarded, it becomes the specification
  -- that the ⊢= body was verified against.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LAYER 3: SELF-APPLICATION
-- cell-zero applied to itself. This closes the metacircular loop.
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- cell-zero can evaluate §cell-zero:
--
--   run(program-path ≡ "cell-zero.cell")
--
-- When this happens:
--   parse reads cell-zero.cell → §graph of cell-zero's own cells
--   find-ready finds which cell-zero cells are ready
--   dispatch evaluates them
--   observe-execution records cell-zero evaluating itself
--   detect-pattern notices: find-ready always produces the same
--     output for the same graph state → classification = "pattern"
--   shadow-verify confirms a ⊢= graph-traversal matches
--   promote replaces find-ready's ∴ with ⊢= topological sort
--
-- This is how cell-zero bootstraps its own parser, its own
-- ready-set computation, its own expression evaluator.
-- Each crystallization makes cell-zero faster and cheaper.
-- The limit: a classical runtime that calls LLM only for ∴ bodies.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- ENVIRONMENT CONTRACT
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- An environment provides implementations for [ENV] cells:
--
--   ⊢ env
--     given environment-name
--     yield §load, §invoke-substrate
--
-- The oracles on load and invoke-substrate are INVARIANT across
-- environments. Only the bodies change.
--
-- | Cell               | single-claude      | hybrid            | gastown              |
-- |--------------------|--------------------|-------------------|----------------------|
-- | load               | human pastes text  | fs.read()         | git.show()           |
-- | invoke-substrate   | LLM does it inline | api.call(claude)  | sling → polecat      |
-- | find-ready         | LLM scans doc      | ⊢= topo-sort      | ⊢= bd ready          |
-- | pick-cell          | LLM chooses        | ⊢= priority queue | ⊢= assignment logic  |
-- | eval-expression    | LLM computes       | ⊢= evaluator      | ⊢= evaluator         |
-- | spawn-children     | LLM describes      | ⊢= template inst  | ⊢= bd create         |
-- | spawn-claims       | LLM describes      | ⊢= from oracles   | ⊢= bd create         |
-- | handle-bottom      | LLM propagates     | ⊢= graph walk     | ⊢= bd update         |
-- | apply-graph-updates| LLM modifies doc   | ⊢= graph merge    | ⊢= bd create + wire  |
-- | observe-execution  | LLM notes it       | ⊢= content hash   | ⊢= bead recording    |
-- | shadow-verify      | LLM compares       | ⊢= comparison     | ⊢= comparison        |
-- | promote            | LLM rewrites cell  | ⊢= AST transform  | ⊢= AST transform    |
--
-- The "single-claude" column is ALL ∴ (soft). Everything else is
-- the crystallization path. The rightmost column is Gas Town, where
-- cell-zero's graph ops map directly to beads infrastructure:
--   find-ready = bd ready
--   spawn-children = bd create
--   apply-graph-updates = bd create + bd dep add
--   observe-execution = bead recording (already built)
--
-- Gas Town was cell-zero's crystallized form before cell-zero existed.


-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- STRUCTURAL REQUIREMENTS SUMMARY
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--
-- § quotation required in three places:
--   1. spawn-children — constructs cell definitions for ⊢⊢ spawners
--   2. spawn-claims   — constructs claim cells from ⊨ oracles
--   3. handle-bottom  — constructs handler cells from ⊥? declarations
--
-- Recursive self-reference required in two places:
--   1. evolution-loop — ⊢∘ requires eval-loop (cell-zero invoking itself)
--   2. check-claims   — evaluating claim cells requires dispatch
--
-- Crystallization required for:
--   cell-zero to stop being an LLM interpreter and become a runtime tool
--
-- Permanently soft cells (never crystallize):
--   dispatch — handles arbitrary ∴ bodies
--   invoke-substrate — IS the semantic substrate call
--   evolution-loop — recursive dispatch over arbitrary cells
--   check-claims — evaluates semantic oracles (∴ claim cells)
--   detect-pattern — generating ⊢= from observed behavior IS semantic
